        </p>
      </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m> and let <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>.
              Explain why <m>n</m> divides <m>a</m> if and only if <m>a \equiv 0 \pmod n</m>.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <m>a \equiv 0 \pmod n</m> if and only if <m>n \mid \left( a - 0 \right)</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="exer_sec34-4b">
            <statement>
            <p>
              Let <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>.
              Explain why if <m>a \not \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>,
              then <m>a \equiv 1\pmod 3</m> or <m>a \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m>.
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Let <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>.
                <xref ref="C_congtorem"></xref>
                tell us that if <m>a \not \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>,
                then <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m> or <m>a \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="exer_sec34-4c">
            <statement>
            <p>
              Is the following proposition true or false?
              Justify your conclusion.
              <blockquote>
                For each <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>, if <m>a \not \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>, then 
                <m>a^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>.
              </blockquote>
            </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <xref ref="exer_sec34-4b"/> tells us we can use a proof by cases using the 
                following two cases: (1)
                <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>; (2) <m>a \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m>.
                So, if <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>,
                then by <xref ref="T_propsofcong"></xref>,
                <m>a \cdot a \equiv 1 \cdot 1 \pmod 3</m>, and hence,
                <m>a^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>.
                If <m>a \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m>,
                then by <xref ref="T_propsofcong"></xref>,
                <m>a \cdot a \equiv 2 \cdot 2 \pmod 3</m>, and hence,
                <m>a^2 \equiv 4 \pmod 3</m>.
                Since <m>4 \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>,
                this implies that <m>a^2 \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>.
              </p>
            </answer>
          </task>

    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="exer_congto3">
      <statement>
        <p>
