          <blockquote>
            For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, if <m>ab \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>, then <m>a \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m> or <m>b \equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>.
          </blockquote>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Use case analysis.
          There are several cases.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The contrapositive is:  Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers. 
          If <m>a \not\equiv 0 \pmod3</m> and
          <m>b \not\equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>, then <m>ab \not\equiv 0 \pmod 3</m>.
          Using <xref ref="exer_sec34-4b"></xref>, we can use the following four cases:
          <ol marker="(1)">
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m> and <m>b \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>a \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m> and <m>b \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <m>a \equiv 2 \pmod 3</m> and <m>b \equiv 1 \pmod 3</m>;
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
